[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] The **front controller** software design pattern is listed in several pattern catalogs and is related to the design of web applications.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] It is "a controller that handles all requests for a website," which is a useful structure for web application developers to achieve flexibility and reuse without code redundancy.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] Front controllers are often used in web applications to implement workflows.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] While not strictly required, it is much easier to control navigation across a set of related pages (for instance, multiple pages used in an online purchase) from a front controller than it is to assign individual pages responsibility for navigation.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] The front controller may be implemented as a Java object, or as a script in a scripting language such as PHP, Raku, Python or Ruby that is called for every request of a web session.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] This script would handle all tasks that are common to the application or the framework, such as session handling, caching and input filtering.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] Based on the specific request, it would then instantiate further objects and call methods to handle the required tasks.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] The alternative to a front controller is the usage of page controllers mapped to each site page or path.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] Although this may cause each individual controller to contain duplicate code, the page-controller approach delivers a high degree of specialization.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] Request processor: used for request processing and modifying or retrieving the appropriate model.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] Flow manager: determines what will be shown on the next page.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] There are three primary benefits associated with the front controller pattern.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] The front controller pattern may incur performance issues because the single controller is performing a great deal of work, and handlers may introduce bottlenecks if they involve database or document queries.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] The front controller approach is also more complex than that of page controllers.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] The data for the application is best handled in a single location, obviating the need for duplicate data-retrieval code.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] Different roles in the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern should be separated to increase testability, which is also true for the controller part in the MVC pattern.
[src:hanami-ruby/front-controller] The page-controller pattern is an alternative to the front controller approach in the MVC model.
[src:hanami-ruby/getting-started] If you’re reading this page, it’s likely you want to learn more about Hanami.
