[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:hanami-ruby/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is interpreted, high-level, and dynamically typed; its interpreter uses garbage collection and just-in-time compilation.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It supports multiple programming paradigms, including procedural, object-oriented, and functional programming.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] According to the creator, Ruby was influenced by Perl, Smalltalk, Eiffel, Ada, BASIC, and Lisp.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] According to Matsumoto, Ruby was conceived in 1993.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto described Ruby's design as resembling a simple Lisp language at its core, with an object system like that of Smalltalk, blocks inspired by higher-order functions, and practical utility like that of Perl.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The name "Ruby" originated during an online chat session between Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka on 24 February 1993, before any code had been written.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Two names were initially proposed: "Coral" and "Ruby".
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto chose the latter in a subsequent email to Ishitsuka.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] He also noted that one factor influencing the choice of the name was that a colleague's birthstone was ruby.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The first public release of Ruby 0.95 was announced on Japanese domestic newsgroups on 21 December 1995.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Subsequently, three more versions of Ruby were released in two days.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The release coincided with the launch of the Japanese-language *ruby-list* mailing list, which was the first mailing list for the new language.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Already present at this stage of development were many of the features familiar in later releases of Ruby, including object-oriented design, classes with inheritance, mixins, iterators, closures, exception handling and garbage collection.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] After the release of Ruby 0.95 in 1995, several stable versions of Ruby were released in these years.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In 1997, the first article about Ruby was published on the Web.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In the same year, Matsumoto was hired by netlab.jp to work on Ruby as a full-time developer.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In 1998, the Ruby Application Archive was launched by Matsumoto, along with a simple English-language homepage for Ruby.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In 1999, the first English language mailing list *ruby-talk* began, which signaled a growing interest in the language outside Japan.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In this same year, Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka wrote the first book on Ruby, *The Object-oriented Scripting Language Ruby* (オブジェクト指向スクリプト言語 Ruby), which was published in Japan in October 1999.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It would be followed in the early 2000s by around 20 books on Ruby published in Japanese.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] By 2000, Ruby was more popular than Python in Japan.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In September 2000, the first English language book *Programming Ruby* was printed, which was later freely released to the public, further widening the adoption of Ruby amongst English speakers.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In early 2002, the English-language *ruby-talk* mailing list was receiving more messages than the Japanese-language *ruby-list*, demonstrating Ruby's increasing popularity in the non-Japanese speaking world.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 was initially released in August 2003, was stable for a long time, and was retired in June 2013.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Although deprecated, there is still code based on it.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 is only partially compatible with Ruby 1.9.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 has been the subject of several industry standards.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It was accepted as a Japanese Industrial Standard (JIS X 3017) in 2011 and an international standard (ISO/IEC 30170) in 2012.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Around 2005, interest in the Ruby language surged in tandem with Ruby on Rails, a web framework written in Ruby.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Rails is frequently credited with increasing awareness of Ruby.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Effective with Ruby 1.9.3, released 31 October 2011, Ruby switched from being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the GPL to being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the two-clause BSD license.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Adoption of 1.9 was slowed by changes from 1.8 that required many popular third party gems to be rewritten.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.0 was intended to be fully backward compatible with Ruby 1.9.3.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] As of the official 2.0.0 release on 24 February 2013, there were only five known incompatibilities.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Starting with 2.1.0, Ruby's versioning policy changed to be more similar to semantic versioning, although it differs slightly in that minor version increments may be API incompatible.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.2.0 includes speed-ups, bugfixes, and library updates and removes some deprecated APIs.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Most notably, Ruby 2.2.0 introduces changes to memory handling – an incremental garbage collector, support for garbage collection of symbols and the option to compile directly against jemalloc.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It also contains experimental support for using vfork(2) with system() and spawn(), and added support for the Unicode 7.0 specification.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Since version 2.2.1, Ruby MRI performance on PowerPC64 was improved.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Features that were made obsolete or removed include callcc, the DL library, Digest::HMAC, lib/rational.rb, lib/complex.rb, GServer, Logger::Application as well as various C API functions.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.3.0 includes many performance improvements, updates, and bugfixes including changes to Proc#call, Socket and IO use of exception keywords, Thread#name handling, default passive Net::FTP connections, and Rake being removed from stdlib.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.4.0 includes performance improvements to hash table, Array#max, Array#min, and instance variable access.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.6.0 include an experimental just-in-time compiler (JIT), and *RubyVM::AbstractSyntaxTree* (experimental).
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.7.0 include pattern Matching (experimental), REPL improvements, a compaction GC, and separation of positional and keyword arguments.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0.0 was released on Christmas Day in 2020.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It is known as Ruby 3x3, which signifies that programs would run three times faster in Ruby 3.0 comparing to Ruby 2.0. and some had already been implemented in intermediate releases on the road from 2 to 3.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] To achieve 3x3, Ruby 3 comes with MJIT, and later YJIT, Just-In-Time Compilers, to make programs faster, although they are described as experimental and remain disabled by default (enabled by flags at runtime).
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Another goal of Ruby 3.0 is to improve concurrency and two more utilities Fibre Scheduler, and experimental Ractor facilitate the goal.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ractor is light-weight and thread-safe as it is achieved by exchanging messages rather than shared objects.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0 introduces RBS language to describe the types of Ruby programs for static analysis.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It is separated from general Ruby programs.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and library changes in Ruby 3.0 as well.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.1 was released on 25 December 2021.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It includes YJIT, a new, experimental, Just-In-Time Compiler developed by Shopify, to enhance the performance of real world business applications.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and other improvements in this release.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Network libraries for FTP, SMTP, IMAP, and POP are moved from default gems to bundled gems.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.2 was released on 25 December 2022.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It brings support for being run inside of a WebAssembly environment via a WASI interface.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Regular expressions also receives some improvements, including a faster, memoized matching algorithm to protect against certain ReDoS attacks, and configurable timeouts for regular expression matching.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Additional debugging and syntax features are also included in this release, which include syntax suggestion, as well as error highlighting.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The MJIT compiler has been re-implemented as a standard library module, while the YJIT, a Rust-based JIT compiler now supports more architectures on Linux.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 was released on 25 December 2023.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 introduces significant enhancements and performance improvements to the language.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Key features include the introduction of the Prism parser for portable and maintainable parsing, the addition of the pure-Ruby JIT compiler RJIT, and major performance boosts in the YJIT compiler.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Additionally, improvements in memory usage, the introduction of an M:N thread scheduler, and updates to the standard library contribute to a more efficient and developer-friendly Ruby ecosystem.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 was released on 25 December 2024.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 adds `it` block parameter reference, changes Prism as default parser, adds Happy Eyeballs Version 2 support to socket library, improves YJIT, adds modular Garbage Collector and so on.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It adds experimental ZJIT, a JIT written in Rust, and experimental "Ruby Box", a feature to provide separation about definitions.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It was decided to bump the version number to 4.0 instead of 3.5 to celebrate Rubys 30. birthday.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto stated that Ruby is designed for programmer productivity and fun, following the principles of good user interface design.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] At a Google Tech Talk in 2008 he said, "I hope to see Ruby help every programmer in the world to be productive, and to enjoy programming, and to be happy.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto has said his primary design goal was to make a language that he himself enjoyed using, by minimizing programmer work and possible confusion.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] If that personal standard remains consistent, there would be few surprises for those familiar with the standard.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is object-oriented: every value is an object, including classes and instances of types that many other languages designate as primitives (such as integers, Booleans, and "null").
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Because everything in Ruby is an object, everything in Ruby has certain built-in abilities called methods.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Every function is a method and methods are always called on an object.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Methods defined at the top level scope become methods of the Object class.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Since this class is an ancestor of every other class, such methods can be called on any object.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] They are also visible in all scopes, effectively serving as "global" procedures.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby supports inheritance with dynamic dispatch, mixins and singleton methods (belonging to, and defined for, a single instance rather than being defined on the class).
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Though Ruby does not support multiple inheritance, classes can import modules as mixins.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It has support for introspection, reflective programming, metaprogramming, and interpreter-based threads.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby features dynamic typing, and supports parametric polymorphism.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] According to the Ruby FAQ, the syntax is similar to Perl's and the semantics are similar to Smalltalk's, but the design philosophy differs greatly from Python's.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The syntax of Ruby is broadly similar to that of Perl and Python.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Class and method definitions are signaled by keywords, whereas code blocks can be defined by either keywords or braces.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In contrast to Perl, variables are not obligatorily prefixed with a sigil.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] When used, the sigil changes the semantics of scope of the variable.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] For practical purposes there is no distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Line breaks are significant and taken as the end of a statement; a semicolon may be equivalently used.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Unlike Python, indentation is not significant.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] One of the differences from Python and Perl is that Ruby keeps all of its instance variables completely private to the class and only exposes them through accessor methods (`attr_writer`, `attr_reader`, etc.).
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Unlike the "getter" and "setter" methods of other languages like C++ or Java, accessor methods in Ruby can be created with a single line of code via metaprogramming; however, accessor methods can also be created in the traditional fashion of C++ and Java.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] As invocation of these methods does not require the use of parentheses, it is trivial to change an instance variable into a full function, without modifying a single line of calling code or having to do any refactoring achieving similar functionality to C# and VB.NET property members.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Python's property descriptors are similar, but come with a trade-off in the development process.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] If one begins in Python by using a publicly exposed instance variable, and later changes the implementation to use a private instance variable exposed through a property descriptor, code internal to the class may need to be adjusted to use the private variable rather than the public property.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby's design forces all instance variables to be private, but also provides a simple way to declare `set` and `get` methods.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] This is in keeping with the idea that in Ruby, one never directly accesses the internal members of a class from outside the class; rather, one passes a message to the class and receives a response.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The original Ruby interpreter is often referred to as Matz's Ruby Interpreter or MRI.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] This implementation is written in C and uses its own Ruby-specific virtual machine.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The standardized and retired Ruby 1.8 implementation was written in C, as a single-pass interpreted language.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Starting with Ruby 1.9, and continuing with Ruby 2.x and above, the official Ruby interpreter has been YARV ("Yet Another Ruby VM"), and this implementation has superseded the slower virtual machine used in previous releases of MRI.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] As of 2026, there are a number of alternative implementations of Ruby, including JRuby, Rubinius, and mruby.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Each takes a different approach, with JRuby and Rubinius providing just-in-time compilation and mruby also providing ahead-of-time compilation.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The maturity of Ruby implementations tends to be measured by their ability to run the Ruby on Rails (Rails) framework, because it is complex to implement and uses many Ruby-specific features.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The point when a particular implementation achieves this goal is called "the Rails singularity".
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The reference implementation, JRuby, and Rubinius are all able to run Rails unmodified in a production environment.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto originally developed Ruby on the 4.3BSD-based Sony NEWS-OS 3.x, but later migrated his work to SunOS 4.x, and finally to Linux.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] By 1999, Ruby was known to work across many different operating systems.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Modern Ruby versions and implementations are available on all major desktop, mobile and server-based operating systems.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is also supported across a number of cloud hosting platforms like Jelastic, Heroku, Google Cloud Platform and others.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Tools such as RVM and RBEnv, facilitate installation and partitioning of multiple ruby versions, and multiple 'gemsets' on one machine.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] A Ruby package is called a "gem" and can be installed via the command line.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Most gems are libraries, though a few exist that are applications, such as IDEs.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] There are over 100,000 Ruby gems hosted on RubyGems.org.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Many new and existing Ruby libraries are hosted on GitHub, a service that offers version control repository hosting for Git.
[src:hanami-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The Ruby Application Archive, which hosted applications, documentation, and libraries for Ruby programming, was maintained until 2013, when its function was transferred to RubyGems.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Modularity is a specific application of concerns to system components (separation by size).
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] In modular systems, each module encapsulates a single concern, and modules are designed, implemented, and understood in isolation before being composed into a larger system.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] While modularity is the most common and recognizable embodiment of SoC in code structure, the principle of Separation of concerns is broader.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] For example, separating requirements analysis from implementation in a project timeline, or separating functional from non-functional requirements in a specification, are valid forms of separation of concerns that do not necessarily require a modular design.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Dijkstra in his 1974 paper *"On the Role of Scientific Thought"*, coined the term *separation of concerns* in relation to software qualities such as *correctness* and *efficiency*.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Carlo Ghezzi in his book "Fundamentals of software engineering" promotes Separation Of Concerns as the primary way to tackle the inherited complexity in software production.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Philippe Kruchten in his article "Architectural Blueprints—The “4+1” View Model of Software Architecture" used a model composed of five main views to address large architectures, essentially this is a view-based separation of concerns, where each view focus on a different aspect of the architecture.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Laplante, Phillip also mentioned that separation of concerns can be applied in software design, coding, time, and software qualities.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] The term *separation of concerns* was probably coined by Edsger W.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Dijkstra in his 1974 paper "On the role of scientific thought".
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Fifteen years later, it was evident the term *separation of concerns* was becoming an accepted idea.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] SoC is crucial to the design of the Internet.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] In the Internet protocol suite, great efforts have been made to separate concerns into well-defined layers.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] This allows protocol designers to focus on the concerns in one layer, and ignore the other layers.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] The Application Layer protocol SMTP, for example, is concerned about all the details of conducting an email session over a reliable transport service (usually TCP), but not in the least concerned about how the transport service makes that service reliable.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Similarly, TCP is not concerned about the routing of data packets, which is handled at the Internet layer.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are complementary languages used in the development of web pages and websites.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] HTML is mainly used for organization of webpage content, CSS is used for definition of content presentation style, and JavaScript defines how the content interacts and behaves with the user.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Historically, this was not the case: prior to the introduction of CSS, HTML performed both duties of defining semantics and style.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Subject-oriented programming allows separate concerns to be addressed as separate software constructs, each on an equal footing with the others.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Each concern provides its own class-structure into which the objects in common are organized, and contributes state and methods to the composite result where they cut across one another.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Correspondence rules describe how the classes and methods in the various concerns are related to each other at points where they interact, allowing composite behavior for a method to be derived from several concerns.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Multi-dimensional SoC allows the analysis and composition of concerns to be manipulated as a multi-dimensional "matrix" in which each concern provides a dimension in which different points of choice are enumerated, with the cells of the matrix occupied by the appropriate software artifacts.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Aspect-oriented programming allows cross-cutting concerns to be addressed as primary concerns.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] For example, most programs require some form of security and logging.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Security and logging are often secondary concerns, whereas the primary concern is often on accomplishing business goals.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] However, when designing a program, its security must be built into the design from the beginning instead of being treated as a secondary concern.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] Applying security afterwards often results in an insufficient security model that leaves too many gaps for future attacks.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] This may be solved with aspect-oriented programming.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] For example, an aspect may be written to enforce that calls to a certain API are always logged, or that errors are always logged when an exception is thrown, regardless of whether the program's procedural code handles the exception or propagates it.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] In cognitive science and artificial intelligence, it is common to refer to David Marr's levels of analysis.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] At any given time, a researcher may be focusing on what some aspect of intelligence needs to compute, what algorithm it employs, or how that algorithm is implemented in hardware.
[src:hanami-ruby/separation-of-concerns] This separation of concerns is similar to the interface/implementation distinction in software and hardware engineering.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:hanami-ruby/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
